title: For Sale:  Sig P250 .45&.357sig
postcontent:
The p250 is a modular pistol, all the moving parts of contained in a metal subframe, that subframe is the part stamped as an actual pistol. Most caliber conversion kits for other guns are just the barrel and spring, in the case of the p250 in also includes the slide and frame, allowing you to not only change caliber, but also frame size, grip size, and barrel/slide length. It is a neat concept, and being as how the serialed part is the subframe new conversion kits can be mailed to your door without going through an ffl. 

What i have for sale is a p250, fullsize, .45 acp, as well as a caliber exchange kit for a subcompact .357sig and a holster for the subcompact. Firearm is accurate, hasn't been broken in completely yet, don't have time for it, just sits in the top of the safe. The pistol i will sell for 400, the conversion kit and holster i will sell for 200, or ill sell everything together for 550.

title: For Sale:  FEG SMC .380 ACP
postcontent:
Short version:

The FEG is a aluminum-framed Hungarian Walther PPK clone. Mine is in great shape, except for a worn magazine. I'm only selling it to get something smaller for daily carry. Make me an offer.

Long version: It is the same size as a PPK or maybe even a little smaller, but lighter because of the frame. It was made in Hungary, imported by K.B.I. The design is a faithful PPK copy; the machining is smooth; the bluing is nice and deep. The gun itself is very reliable and accurate. There's nothing fussy about it. I've only put between 300 or 400 rounds through it (yay ammo shortage) and used it as my CCW for 5 months. I added tiny orange dots on the tiny sights, which does help the sight picture, but you can take those off if you want.

I love this gun. I just need something smaller. The only beef I could think of with the body of it is that the mag release doesn't spit it out with energy, just lets go so you can pull it out.

The magazine is worn. The metal is too soft and the top edges that feed the bullet get splayed apart with daily unloading and reloading, which could then feeding/ejection issues. A quick squeeze with some pliers fixes it temporarily, but it's going to keep happening with enough use. You should probably replace the mag if you're going to use it daily.

Make me an offer!
